article.description: Reserve Tye'sha Fluker scored 10 points, helping No. 5 Tennessee to a 66-42 win over Old Dominion on Sunday.
article.headline: Summitt trails only Smith, Rupp in wins
article.linkText: Lady Vols move Summitt into third for career wins
article.story:
KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Tennessee coach Pat Summitt has a new
gold and diamond ring and another win to move up on the list of
career college basketball victories.

Reserve Tye'sha Fluker scored 10 points and Tasha Butts and
reserve Shanna Zolman each had nine, helping the No. 5 Lady Vols to
a 66-42 win over Old Dominion on Sunday.

Summitt was presented the ring by Wendy Larry, Old Dominion's
coach and president of the Women's Basketball Coaches Association,
on behalf of the organization and in honor of her 800th coaching
win, a mark the Tennessee coach reached last January.

Summitt moved into third place on the career victory list with
831, surpassing retired Mount St. Mary's coach Jim Phelan. Summitt
trails Dean Smith (879) and Adolph Rupp (876). Texas coach Jody
Conradt, whose Longhorns beat Tennessee last weekend, is fifth with
829.

After the presentation, the Lady Vols (10-1) had little trouble
earning their eighth straight win over Larry's Lady Monarchs (6-5).

Shyra Ely and Ashley Robinson added eight points apiece for
Tennessee, which led nearly the entire game and pulled away with a
9-4 run at the start of the second half.

The Lady Monarchs got as close as 13 with 13:50 remaining, after
Shareese Grant had two layups, but Tennessee responded with a 6-0
run.

Robinson got a putback, and Zolman scored off a steal by Butts.
Then Loree Moore grabbed a rebound and rushed to the basket,
bouncing the ball to Butts to give her an easy layup.

Summitt has 28 victories over Old Dominion in a series that
dates to 1977.

"I look back to the AIAW days. We played each other in a lot of
regional finals and Final Fours," she said. "They made us a lot
better earlier. When you look at women's basketball, the evolution
of the game, Old Dominion played a big part in what is happening."

The Lady Monarchs shot just 16-of-57 from the floor and had 22
turnovers. Tennessee had a better day shooting, but neither team
could get to the foul line, combining for 11-of-24 free-throw
shooting.

Ely, Tennessee's leading scorer, had all of her points in the
first half and shot just 3-for-11 from the field. Tennessee didn't
have a player score in double figures until Fluker's basket with
1:45 left.

"I feel good about having a blowout," Butts said. "You don't
have to worry about who's going to shoot the last shot or who's
going to get in trouble the next day at practice."

The Lady Monarchs, coming off a tough 69-45 loss at Rutgers last
week, were led in scoring by Monique Coker with 10 points. Lawona
Davis had nine. Grant, who came in averaging a team-high 17.6
points, was held to eight.

"I thought we got down on ourselves easily," Larry said. "We
have a tendency to sulk."

The Lady Vols took the lead at 8-7 and never let it go. Old
Dominion got as close as three midway through the first half, but
poor shooting prevented the Lady Monarchs from sustaining a rally.

Tennessee went ahead by nine with 4:05 left before halftime
after Robinson's layup.

Davis converted a three-point play to cut it to 25-19 for Old
Dominion, but the Lady Vols finished the first half with a 7-1 run
to go ahead 32-20.
